                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d97">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">838.00Electoral Law/12: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Chargé in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gross</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-09-16T15:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 16, 1927—3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>74. You will inform President Borno that Department would be pleased to have
                    opportunity to examine proposed electoral law before it is acted upon by Council
                    of State.</p>
                <pb facs="0180" n="78" xml:id="pg_78"/>
                <p>Department prefers not to give opinion at present on modification relating to
                    personnel of boards of each district. This matter appears to be one of internal
                    administration which should affect in no way the successful carrying out of
                    treaty provisions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Carr</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
